# 🐿️ GoneSquirrel.io — Vision & Reference

> **Purpose of this document**: Reference guide for iterating from the current FluidCalendar fork toward the GoneSquirrel.io vision. Used by Claude Code to evaluate proposed changes against the destination, and by future-Seneca to remember what "good" looks like when 11pm hyperfocus tries to add a streak counter.

> **How to use this**: When proposing or evaluating any change, ask three questions:
> 1. Does it move us toward the vision in this doc, away from it, or sideways?
> 2. Does it violate any of the ADHD-Native Interaction Rules?
> 3. Is the cost (build time, complexity, maintenance) worth the distance gained?

> **What this document is NOT**: A build plan. A spec. A promise to ship every feature listed. It's a north star. Some features here may never get built, and that's fine.

---

## 1. CURRENT STATE & STARTING POINT

This project began as a fork of [FluidCalendar](https://github.com/dotnetfactory/fluid-calendar) — an open-source Motion alternative built in Next.js 15 + Prisma + Postgres. The fork was chosen over a from-scratch build for two reasons: time-to-working-tool, and the hard infrastructure (calendar OAuth, scheduling primitives, FullCalendar UI) was already solved.

**What FluidCalendar gives us out of the box:**
- Google Calendar / Outlook / CalDAV integration
- Task auto-scheduling with energy-level inputs
- Focus Mode (passive task selector)
- Project organization, tags, priorities
- Self-hostable via Docker
- Next.js + Prisma + Postgres stack

**What we changed first** (foundational fixes, see WORKING_NOTES.md for specifics):
- Calendar sync no longer cuts off mid-month
- Auto-scheduler now respects user-defined work hours
- Auto-scheduler now matches task energy to time-of-day energy preferences

**What we're iterating toward**: An ADHD-native, voice-friendly, ClickUp-integrated productivity layer with a distinctive brand voice and a Now Mode that captures motivation in real time. The destination is described in the rest of this document.

