## 8. DATA MODEL VISION

FluidCalendar's existing Prisma schema is the starting point. We extend it rather than replace it.

### New columns on existing `tasks` table (when needed)
- `energy_level` — already supported by FluidCalendar in some form, verify and align
- `task_type` enum: deep_work / light_work / admin / creative / physical / personal
- `external_source` — for ClickUp/Jira/etc integration ('clickup', 'jira', null)
- `external_id`, `external_url`, `external_metadata jsonb`
- `last_synced_at`, `sync_status`
- `needs_clarification bool` — for Stash entries
- Status value `'stash'` added to enum (rename of `brain_dump`)

### New tables (when those features land)
- `pomodoro_sessions` — task_id, started_at, ended_at, duration, was_completed, interruption_count
- `notifications_log` — type, payload, sent_at, action_taken (for adaptive frequency)
- `integration_syncs` — provider config, scope, sync state
- `integration_sync_log` — per-event audit trail
- `user_preferences` extensions — energy_peaks jsonb, dnd_start/end, daily_planning_time, voice_enabled

### What to preserve from FluidCalendar
Their calendar event tables, OAuth token storage, project structures, schedule blocks, NextAuth schema. Don't refactor what works.

